<DOCNO> AP890421-0008 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a beloved leader dies thousands march to 
beijings central square to express grief and anger the 
government afraid suppresses them 
the scenario played out 13 years ago in what became known as 
the tiananmen incident is being repeated with haunting 
similarities as students mourn former communist party chief hu 
yaobang and demand political reforms 
there are also striking differences reflecting changes that 
have made china a more open and slightly more tolerant society 
in april 1976 the mourning was for premier chou enlai 
regarded by many as the last voice of reason and moderation in an 
age of political insanity known as the cultural revolution 
chou died of cancer in january 1976 revolutionary leader mao 
tsetung was on his deathbed power was in the hands of the 
ultraleftist faction headed by maos wife jiang qing which came 
to be called the gang of four 
the leftists attempted to stifle mourning for chou but during 
the april qingming festival the traditional time for chinese to 
honor their dead there was a spontaneous outpouring of grief 
on april 2 about 10000 people marched to tiananmen square to 
lay wreaths in honor of chou compose poems mourning his death and 
make speeches with thinly veiled criticisms of jiang qings group 
the party ordered citizens to stay away from the square the 
response was defiance 
on april 3 more than 100000 congregated there and the 
monument to revolutionary heroes in the center of the plaza was 
piled high with wreaths 
the following night authorities removed all the wreaths and on 
april 5 events turned violent angry crowds overturned a police van 
and burned several cars and a police command post the militia 
attacked beating with staves and dragging people off 
figures vary but some witnesses say 100 were killed and 3000 
to 4000 arrested 
when mao died five months later militaryled opponents of jiang 
qing moved in quickly and overthrew the gang of four 
like chou hu yaobang was known as a man of the people a victim 
of the cultural revolution he helped redress wrongs done during 
that period 
hu also won the sympathy of students after he was ousted as 
party chief in january 1987 for failing to deal harshly with 
prodemocracy student demonstrations 
after he died of a heart attack april 15 thousands trooped to 
tiananmen square to lay wreaths write poems and give speeches 
criticizing the nations leaders 
but hus popularity was limited mainly to intellectuals unlike 
chou who was beloved by all sectors of society and discontent 
with the pace of political reform today in no way compares to the 
hatreds engendered by the cultural revolutions leadership 
although hu is genuinely respected there have not been the 
tears and deep sense of personal loss there was for chou 
i dont think hu was a savior for the country said one 
beijing university student but we needed something to spur 
people into action she said 
many students interviewed also acknowledged that unlike in 1976 
there is no broadbased support for their protests 
chous death brought out factory workers farmers professionals 
and people of all ages 
workers have listened with sympathy to the students but few 
have joined them in demonstrations 
you cant eat democracy said one worker who argued that 
slowing the 36 percent inflation rate not instituting political 
reforms should be the nations main concern 
and although police have kicked and hit a few students they are 
not likely to resort to such largescale beatings as in 1976 the 
government is more conscious of public and international opinion 
and students worried about their futures are unlikely to press too 
far 
participants in the tiananmen incident of 1989 also know that 
unlike their predecessors they are not going to change the world 
weve tried before to demonstrate for free speech and 
failed said one demonstrator this time too the results will 
not be good 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

