<TEXT>
a senate committee is taking a look at the 
impact of 10 years of airline deregulation on fares and competition 
the senate commerce science and transportation committee sent 
letters thursday to transportation secretary samuel skinner and 
attorney general dick thornburgh raising several questions about 
the decreasing number of airlines and the increasing cost of 
airplane tickets 
in my view economic concentration and monopoly power are at 
the heart of the problem said sen john c danforth of missouri 
ranking republican on the committee the letters were signed by 
danforth committee chairman ernest hollings dsc and sens 
wendell ford dky and john mccain rariz both leaders of the 
aviation subcommittee 
the senators said that while 215 airlines were created over the 
last decade only 59 still exist and eight carriers now control 94 
percent of the us air travel market 
the committee also has asked the general accounting office the 
investigative arm of congress to analyze the impact of decreased 
competition in its study of fares at 15 large and small hubs around 
the country a congressional source said the committee plans to 
hold a hearing on airline competition next month 
the letters to skinner and thornburgh raise strong concerns 
about performance of the aviation industry since deregulation in 
1978 
the inquiry follows a transportation department study in january 
that showed air fares have increased substantially since 1985 at a 
half dozen airports dominated by a single airline the study showed 
aboveaverage increases at st louis charlotte nc cincinnati 
detroit minneapolis raleigh nc and salt lake city 
the senators asked skinner to say whether he considers the 
concentration consistent with the goals of deregulation whether it 
can be reversed and whether he supports the purchase of interest in 
us airlines by foreign carriers 
they also asked several questions about the apparent link 
between high fares and increasing singleairline domination of hub 
airports about the effects of deregulation on service to smaller 
communities about airline profits and about other matters 
affecting competition 
the senators asked thornburgh if the justice department believes 
action should be taken to encourage more competition particularly 
at hub airports 
questions for thornburgh cover department policy on the 
application of antitrust laws to airlines on international mergers 
involving us airlines on airline control over hub airports on 
longterm leases of gates and other airport facilities on sharing 
arrangements between major airlines and regional carriers and on 
department authority to challenges predatory pricing and 
discriminatory pricing by airlines 
