<TEXT>
despite a declining rate of spina bifida cases in 
the united states the birth defect still leaves thousands of 
american children struggling to live with its effects often at 
tremendous cost 
the national centers for disease control predicted thursday that 
by the end of 1990 the united states will have 13000 children 
born with spina bifida in the 1980s and still living at an annual 
cost of nearly 100 million 
each year about 1500 children are born in the united states 
with spina bifida the incomplete closing of the bony structure 
surrounding the spinal cord more than 1000 survive the newborn 
days and enter childhood the cdc said in its weekly report 
an estimated 9800 children born with spina bifida between 1980 
and 1987 were still alive in 1987 and by the end of 1990 that 
number is expected to grow to an estimated 13000 
in 1990 the average annual cost for medical and surgical care 
for all surviving children born with spina bifida since 1980 will 
approach 100 million the atlantabased cdc reported further 
the number of surviving spina bifida patients born before 1980 is 
as large as those born after 1980 it is likely that their 
costs would equal or exceed those of the post1980 patients 
spina bifida often strikes along with anencephaly the absence 
of major parts of the brain in that case most patients die a few 
hours after birth for the spina bifida patients who survive life 
is expensive 
infants with spina bifida routinely receive vigorous medical 
therapy and undergo repeated surgical procedures to survive and 
reach their maximum functional capacity the cdc said noting 
that the lifetime costs for such a patient can reach 250000 
the cause of spina bifida is still unknown but the disease rate 
is decreasing from a rate of 52 cases per 10000 births in 1980 
to 43 in 1987 nobody really knows why said dr david 
erickson a cdc birth defects specialist 
some of the decrease is due to new hightechnology prenatal 
testing which gives more mothers the option of terminating problem 
pregnancies but that doesnt explain all of it erickson said 
