<TEXT>
a newborn california condor chick gobbled down 
its first meal of minced mice and egg yolk and was pronounced alert 
and healthy by its anxious keepers 
an eyedropper was used thursday to give the bird its first meal 
said tom hanscom spokesman for the san diego wild animal park the 
bird hatched wednesday is the second california condor to be 
conceived and produced in captivity and the 29th known member of 
the critically endangered species 
the initial feeding was withheld until thursday to give the 
chick named mandan time to rest and build an appetite while being 
monitored by keepers for signs of a working digestive system 
it gobbled it down it did so well with the first feeding that 
it took two minced mice about an hour later hanscom said the 
chick is alert and active and gives every appearance of a healthy 
baby condor 
the 69ounce chick was named after an indian tribe native to 
the eastern rockies where condors lived hundreds of years ago it 
is the offspring of the same condor couple that produced molloko 
the yearold condor that was the first of the species conceived and 
born in captivity 
mandans sex will be determined in several weeks when its 
strong enough to undergo a blood test its hatching gives hope for 
the future of north americas largest land birds which have 
wingspans up to 9 feet hanscom said 
three other fertile condor eggs incubating at the park are 
expected to hatch at various times within the next six weeks 
all california condors known to exist are in the states two 
condor breeding stations fifteen birds are at the wild animal park 
and 14 at the los angeles zoo 
