<TEXT>
the air force mismanaged development of the 
nations satellite tracking and warning system contend 
congressional investigators who are calling on lawmakers to stop 
funding for the 437 million project until problems are resolved by 
the pentagon 
the air force has invested over 235 million in a system that 
is now more than four years behind schedule and far from meeting 
its required operational capability the general accounting 
office the investigative arm of congress said in a report 
the gao evaluated the services attempts to modernize the us 
space commands space surveillance and attack assessment subsystem 
known as the space defense operations center 
the system which is located at the cheyenne mountain air force 
station in colorado springs colo is a data processing and 
communications center designed to monitor about 10000 manmade 
objects in space provide warnings of any military attack in space 
and protect satellites from attack 
the subsystem is considered key to the operation of the north 
american aerospace defense command or norad which is responsible 
for alerting the united states and canada if north america is under 
air missile or space attack 
the gao said that over a fiveyear period the air force ignored 
warnings from technical contractors that the program would have 
difficulty achieving its requirements 
specifically the contractor expressed concerns about the 
systems security design deficiencies in the model used to predict 
performance and overall software design quality 
in response to the report which was released this week the 
defense department admitted that the initial phase of the system 
cannot perform 14 of 23 originally required missions 
but the department said it believes the air force has taken 
the necessary action to ensure that the later phases of the 
program avoid the pitfalls that have hampered the effort to date 
the air force plans to spend about 437 million on the project 
a substantial increase over its original estimate of 290 million 
previous estimates that the entire system would be operating by 
june 1988 also have changed 
the air force says the system will not be completed until fiscal 
1994 
the gao urged congress to withhold additional funds for the 
project until the defense acquisition board and defense secretary 
dick cheney have approved plans to meet the investigators 
recommendations 
