shipments of consumer goods sell out quickly and many items are 
hard to find 
a senior government statistician revealed friday the problem is 
worsening 
average wages rose 95 percent in the first three months of 
1989 compared with the same period a year earlier but 
productivity increased just 45 percent and consumer goods 
production rose 58 percent said nikolai g belov first deputy 
chief of the state statistics board 
soviet statistics unlike western ones do not account for 
inflation 
wages have risen much faster than projected much faster than 
productivity of labor which adversely affects the market 
situation belov said 
the average wage of soviet workers jumped from 347 to 379 a 
month in the first three months belov said 
as a result of the deficit of goods soviets are saving massive 
amounts of money belov said about 497 billion is being kept in 
savings accounts and is out of circulation 
medvedev the member of the ruling politburo responsible for 
ideology culture and propaganda said that without a hard 
stable ruble the whole system of economic regulators cannot work 
the soviet rubleexchange rate is set by the government at 162 
per ruble but the black market rate is 12 cents to 25 cents per 
ruble 
medvedev also said the move toward a more marketoriented 
economy is proceeding slower than desired factories are supposed 
to be developing their own suppliers and customers instead of 
depending on centralized allocations 
he also cited pricing and the government deficit as key 
problems soviet prices are set by bureaucrats with no regard to 
cost of production the budget deficit is estimated at 160 billion 
this year 
the ideologist emphasized the justice of paying people according 
