<TEXT>
a federal appeals court friday upheld a 
federal communications commission policy giving preference to women 
and minorities trying to gain broadcasting licenses 
the decision by a threejudge panel of the us court of appeals 
for the district of columbia followed a march 31 ruling by another 
panel of judges at the court that found a companion fcc minority 
preference policy was unconstitutional 
the case acted on friday was brought by metro broadcasting and 
winter park communications over the awarding of a television 
license to rainbow broadcasting in the orlando fla area 
rainbow was granted the license when its high percentage of 
minority ownership outweighed factors favoring metro particularly 
how well the metro owners were integrated into the stations 
management 
writing for the panel judge harry t edwards said the case 
closely paralleled a 1984 case involving west michigan broadcasting 
co in which this court expressly held that the fccs use of an 
enhancement for minority status easily passes constitutional 
muster 
fcc spokeswoman maureen peratino said commission chairman dennis 
patrick would have no comment on the decision 
andrew schwartzman executive director of the media access 
project hailed the ruling 
this is a sound policy promoting core democratic values and a 
sound decision upholding it schwartzman said 
the justice department had intervened on behalf of the 
plaintiffs 
the case began in 1983 when an administrative law judge first 
awarded the license to metro after disqualifing rainbow for lack 
of candor in its application 
rainbow and winter park appealed to an fcc review board which 
reversed the judge on the candor issue and awarded the license to 
rainbow the judge said rainbow had 90 percent hispanic ownership 
participation whereas metro had only one 198 percent partner who 
was black 
the board said the minority and slight female ownership 
advantage outweighed factors in metros favor 
after metro and winter park appealed to the court the fcc in 
1986 began reviewing its comparative preference policies it found 
that absent rainbows minority advantages rainbow would not have 
gotten the license over metro 
on dec 22 1987 thenpresident reagan signed an appropriations 
measure in which congress forbade the fcc from spending any money 
to continue the reexamination of or change its minority policies 
winter park argued it should have been given the license in 
order to establish the first tv station in the community of winter 
park where it also would have served orlando along with five other 
stations there the court rejected winter parks argument and 
assessed the minority preference issues 
edwards and judge daniel m friedman concurred in the ruling 
while judge stephen f williams agreed in part and dissented in 
part 
in his dissent williams said the west michigan decision to 
make race pivotal in license allocations had been undermined 
by more recent supreme court decisions on minority setaside 
programs 
the appeals court in its march 31 ruling had thrown out the 
fccs socalled distress sale policy which allowed broadcasters in 
jeopardy of losing their licenses to quickly sell to a minority 
enterprise at 75 percent of the stations fair market value 
</TEXT>
