<TEXT>
a huge c130 cargo plane carrying 15 
tons of corn landed in the southern sudanese city of torit on 
friday as the united nations started up relief operations after a 
deadly ambush caused a threeday delay 
paul mitchell a spokesman for the united nations operation 
lifeline sudan told the associated press the plane arrived safely 
in the beleaguered town after leaving ugandas entebbe airport 
before dawn 
a 47truck relief convoy carrying 1100 tons to southern sudan 
also began friday with the first trucks rolling out of kampala 
before noon said gote hertz a un spokesman in kampala 
mitchell said the c130 leased from and operated by the 
miamibased southern air transport company will make three flights 
daily to torit until it has delivered 1100 tons 
the airlift and convoy are part of a massive 132 million un 
effort to stock more than 110000 tons of food and supplies in 
wartorn southern sudan before heavy seasonal rains begin in four 
weeks 
the operation hopes to avoid a repetition of last years 
tragedy when up to 500000 people died of famine induced by 
drought floods and a rebellion by the sudan peoples liberation 
army 
the liberation army began its rebellion in early 1983 demanding 
greater autonomy and economic reforms in the three southern 
provinces of bahr ghazal upper nile and equatoria 
the first un convoy in rebelheld southern sudan was ambushed 
on tuesday as it traveled west to torit from the sudan peoples 
liberation army base of kapoeta eight rebel escorts were killed 
and the lead truck was destroyed un officials have not assessed 
blame but suspicion fell on tribal raiders government troops or 
government militias fighting the rebels 
mitchell said fridays flight represented the start of the first 
significant shipment of relief food to torit the norwegian 
peoples aid and world vision relief agencies have delivered just 
under 100 tons to torit since april 1 he said 
the c130 until tuesday was one of two planes carrying food into 
the southern sudanese provincial capital of juba which is 
continuing to receive 55 tons of relief supplies daily on the 
remaining c130 said hertz 
he said the truck convoy will head first to the sudanese border 
town of nimule and leave perhaps 110 tons of food and supplies for 
an unknown number of displaced people there said hertz 
from nimule it will continue on to torit only if convoy leaders 
believe conditions are safe and no threat exists of land mines 
along the route he said 
in recent weeks torits civilian population swelled from 3000 
to 25000 as displaced southerners pour in from the surrounding 
bush un officials expect the population to climb to 50000 in 
the coming weeks 
