<TEXT>
frank susmans commitment to abortion rights 
began 20 years ago when as a legal volunteer for a suicide 
hotline he realized how many women with unwanted pregnancies were 
considering killing themselves 
this week that commitment takes him before the us supreme 
court to argue the most important abortion case since the procedure 
was legalized in 1973 
on wednesday susman will present oral arguments against a 
missouri law that he and other prochoice advocates believe poses a 
serious threat to abortion rights the antiabortion side will be 
argued by missouri attorney general william webster in support of 
the law and harvard professor charles fried representing the bush 
administration which seeks to overturn the landmark roe vs wade 
decision of 1973 
clearly this is the greatest threat to womens liberty in 
those 16 years said the 47yearold susman who acknowledges 
feeling great pressure you spend most of your time thinking 
cogitating meditating just thinking about it and reshuffling the 
cards 
it was in the late 1960s and early 70s that susman working as 
a volunteer lawyer for suicide prevention inc realized the 
anguish of women with unwanted pregnancies 
it was difficult then as it is now to imagine anything as 
horrendous as being pregnant and not wanting to be he said in an 
interview friday 
that work led him to help another group that assisted women 
seeking legal abortions out of state or illegal abortions locally 
i had never known a person who had had an abortion until 
then he said 
susman has argued abortion cases before the supreme court 
before but never one as potentially damaging to abortion rights as 
webster vs reproductive health services 
the missouri law passed in 1986 restricts abortion by banning 
the procedure in publicly funded hospitals and forbidding the use 
of public funds and declares that human life begins at conception 
the law was blocked from going into effect by a classaction 
suit led by reproductive health services of st louis planned 
parenthood of greater kansas city and others 
the us district court in kansas city declared major sections 
of the law unconstitutional the 8th us circuit court of appeals 
upheld the decision the supreme court agreed earlier this year to 
hear the case 
susman who represents about 20 abortion clinics nationwide on a 
