themselves by putting down local roots 
but many japanese perceive pickens as making an attempt at 
greenmail taking a company hostage with the intention of selling 
it at a profit rather than managing it for the long run 
this is a bad example of an american acquisition a 
corporate activist with no expertise in the business buying up 
shares in a company said yoshihisa murasawa a consultant with 
booz allen hamilton japan inc 
mergers and acquisitions have shown signs of picking up the 
number of securities firms have been reduced through such tactics 
from 600 a decade ago to 250 today murasawa said 
but he said japanese lack a habit of buying and selling 
companies 
