<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commission asked an 
appeals court friday to consider a legal maneuver that could break 
the logjam blocking final approval of the massive drexel burnham 
lambert inc settlement 
the sec and drexel asked the appeals court to clarify or 
reconsider its earlier ruling which blocks us district judge 
milton pollack from considering a plan to settle the biggest 
securities fraud case in history 
the sec and drexel are now asking the 2nd us circuit court of 
appeals whether another district court judge could consider the 
tentative settlement 
pollack is barred from approving the drexelsec settlement or 
conducting any further proceedings in the case pending a bid to 
disqualify him for an alleged conflict of interest 
in addition to delaying settlement of the secs civil action 
against drexel the 2nd circuit ruling also holds up drexels plea 
agreement with federal prosecutors requiring the investment 
banking giant to plead guilty to six felony counts and pay 650 
million in fines and penalties 
on wednesday the 2nd circuit unanimously refused to modify its 
earlier stay against any action by pollack but the appeals court 
did not address the secs alternative proposal to let another judge 
handle the matter 
in washington sec solicitor paul gonson said the commission was 
asking the 2nd circuit to clear up any ambiguity or to 
reconsider that part of the initial request not mentioned in its 
wednesday ruling 
the sec joined by drexel and cary j maultasch a drexel 
employee named in the sec action asked the appeals court whether 
it would consider allowing the judge sitting in part i the section 
handling miscellaneous and emergency actions to handle the 
settlement 
wednesdays ruling made no reference at all to the part i 
judge said gonson the reasoning in that order didnt appear 
to undercut the authority of the part i judge 
the challenge to pollack first came from drexel which has since 
withdrawn its objection drexel lawyers maintained pollack should 
be disqualified because his wife stood to make millions from a 
leveraged buyout that drexel had helped to finance 
but the matter is now being pressed by former drexel junk bond 
chief michael milken and his brother lowell who are not part of 
either settlement the us supreme court has not yet decided 
whether to consider the milkens appeal but the process could delay 
final approval of the settlement for months 
the milkens were named earlier this month in a massive federal 
racketeering indictment seeking more than 18 billion in 
forfeitures they have pleaded innocent 
last week drexel and the sec asked the 2nd circuit to modify the 
stay but the appeals court said allowing pollack to consider and 
possibly to approve this settlement would be to allow a change in 
the status quo as it concerns the interests of michael and lowell 
milken before the supreme court has disposed of the case 
in seeking clarification of that order gonson noted that the 
only issue before the supreme court in the milkens appeal is 
whether judge pollack can remain on the case and turning the 
case over to another judge would bypass the rule barring the 2nd 
circuit from altering a stay until the high court has decided 
