<TEXT>
whittle communications lp sent out the last of 
its experimental television news shows for teens on friday but 
wont decide until midsummer if the commerciallysponsored project 
passed or failed its test 
the channel one news program a daily 12minute newscast with 
two minutes of product advertising per show has been beamed by 
satellite over the past seven weeks to six middle and high schools 
the program has proven popular with many of the teachers 
principals and students in the six test schools but it has drawn 
criticism from some national education groups who object to 
permitting paid pitches for shampoo candy bars sneakers and jeans 
in the classroom 
we thought a lot of the program said stan jasinskas 
principal at eisenhower middle school in kansas city kan one of 
the test schools we think it probably ought to be continued 
nationally 
ed winter the whittle partner in charge of the channel one 
project said it may take two months or more to evaluate results of 
the test and if it is feasible to expand the program nationally he 
expects a decision by midsummer 
the projects initial goal was to make the program and the 
equipment available to as many as 10000 schools in the fall of 
1990 if it does that channel one would be knoxville tennbased 
whittle communications largest single business 
the speciality magazine and sponsored poster publisher had 
revenue of about 150 million last year and estimates channel one 
could produce 100 million in revenue on its own 
the channel one test began on march 6 at eisenhower middle 
school and at high schools in knoxville tenn cincinnati 
billerica mass detroit and cerritos calif 
in addition to 25 daily shows with advertising whittle provided 
fourpage course guides for teachers a commercialfree live 
broadcast of a space shuttle launch and several public broadcasting 
system programs 
in addition to criticism over subjecting students to product 
ads some educators have faulted the way channel one is presented 
scott thomson executive director of the national association of 
secondary school principals said research has indicated the best 
way to use television as a teaching aid is to use it selectively as 
part of a lesson 
but he said channel one fails to do that because it is beamed 
schoolwide at a regular time of the day without regard to whether 
the program fits in with whatever class may follow 
thomson said he is not surprised that the administrators at the 
test schools speak highly of the program you cant expect them 
to say ive made a poor professional judgment he said 
the test schools get to keep the equipment whittle installed no 
