describing the oil industrys contingency spill response plan 
skinner said on the scale of one to 10 it was a zero 
the big soviet skimmer ship was called in because the small 
boats available in alaska can handle seas only to about 5 feet 
seas in the gulf of alaska recently have run as high as 12 feet 
bigger skimmers werent built because cleanup contingency 
planners didnt expect oil to get outside prince william sound 
which is largely protected from rough waves by a series of islands 
the vaidogubsky is the worlds largest oilskimming vessel it 
is owned by the far eastern sea oil and gas deepdrilling 
organization a governmentowned enterprise the ship can pick up 
800 cubic meters of sludge per hour with booms and two pumps 
the soviet ship was working in conjunction with the us coast 
guard but state officials relinquished command to exxon of a fleet 
of more than 300 other vessels engaged in the cleanup they said 
the move was to improve coordination 
jim hayden of the state department of environmental conservation 
said monitors will be placed on larger vessels to make sure exxons 
claims of oil recovered arent exaggerated and the number of dead 
animals isnt undercounted 
state environmental conservation commissioner dennis kelso said 
exxon claims to have recovered 13 percent of the 101 million 
gallons spilled but he said the figure probably includes seawater 
sucked up with the oil 
the oil has gotten progressively more difficult to clean up as 
it congeals from the effects on wind and water two coast guard 
skimmers were knocked out of action when the sludge fouled their 
pumps 
exxon says the recovered oil will be mixed with fresh north 
slope crude and taken to west coast refineries to be turned into 
heating oil and asphalt 
