pacific telesis group in a move that could 
set off a major legal squabble said thursday it had agreed in 
principle to acquire an option to buy an interest in the chicago 
cable television properties owned by group w 
the move if approved would mark the first time one of the baby 
bell telephone companies has entered the cable television field 
pacific telesis said an affiliate of prime cable of austin 
texas has an agreement in principle which it expects to be 
finalized next month to buy group ws chicago cable television 
assets for 198 million 
prime also has agreed in principle to sell a 68 percent interest 
in the properties to a financial partner which similarly has 
agreed to sell its interest to pacific telesis group if the phone 
company receives regulatory and legal approval 
james mooney president of the national cable television 
association in washington dc said his group would fight the 
pacific telesis proposal he said it appeared to violate the 1984 
federal consent decree under which american telephone amp telegraph 
co spun off its local telephone operations such as pacific 
telesis into seven regional holding companies informally called 
baby bells 
we support the consent decree which is premised on 
justifiable fears of telephone companies using their huge monopoly 
phone business to crosssubsidize and otherwise impede competition 
and therefore intend to oppose the granting of a waiver mooney 
said 
the consent decree prohibited the seven baby bells from 
competing in information services businesses such as home banking 
shopping or electronic yellow pages the decree also prohibited the 
phone companies from owning cable tv programming out of concern 
that the companies could use their monopoly telephone earning 
powers to price cable tv services unfairly 
nonbell companies such as general telephone in california a 
division of gte corp are allowed to operate cable systems outside 
the telephone companies local service areas the federal 
communications commission last year granted gte a waiver to that 
crossownership rule allowing gte to build a cable system in the 
los angeles suburb of cerritos 
ncta has challenged that waiver and the fcc is scheduled to 
consider the challenge next week 
group ws chicago cable operation serves more than 97000 
subscribers in a franchise area encompassing 410000 homes 
we believe cable television is a promising line of business 
for us said sam ginn chairman and chief executive officer of 
pacific telesis 
the department of justice has approved the terms of pacific 
telesis proposed option and is notifying us district judge 
harold h greene who oversaw the atampt breakup of the approval 
the corporation expects to file a waiver request with the court 
this summer 
last year pacific telesis invested in cable television 
operations in london with jones intercable inc as its partner 
the divestiture agreement that outlines what types of businesses 
the regional telephone holding companies may pursue in the united 
states requires a company requesting a waiver to show that there 
is no substantial possibility that it could use its monopoly power 
to impede competition in the market it seeks to enter 
ginn said he is optimistic about the prospects for receiving a 
waiver 
we dont see how we could use our telephone exchange 
position in california to impede competition in illinois in any 
way he said 
